Introduction

Homework 1 is an introduction to sports forecasting where we are asked to observe and analyze the behaviours of different betting companies and leagues with the use of information from the two data sets -data_matches and data_odds- (odds from different betting companies, scores of the matches etc.).

data_matches <- readRDS("/Users/elifkonyar/Desktop/IE 582/HW1/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_matches.rds")
data_odds <- readRDS("/Users/elifkonyar/Desktop/IE 582/HW1/df9b1196-e3cf-4cc7-9159-f236fe738215_odd_details.rds")

Task 1

The objective of this task is to understand if bookmakers perform well in setting their odds for over and under bets. For over/under bets, 2.5 is chosen as the threshold. This information can be found in totalhandicap column in the data_odds data set.

The data set contains the odds information. Therefore, the over and under probabilities have to be calculated based on the existing odds. The implied over probabilities for this task can be calculated as:

implied_prob_over=prob_over*(1/prob_over+prob_under)

where prob_over can be calculated simply by 1/odd_over, and prob_under similarly.

The strategy in evaluating the performance of the bookmakers is as follows:

  1. Determining a probability range (a)
  2. Counting the games that finished over and that have the implied over probability in corresponding bin (b)
  3. Counting the total number of games in the corresponding bin (c)
  4. Calculating the estimated probability of overs ((b)/(c))
  5. Calculating the implied over probability average in each bin.

In the whole homework, the bin range is taken as 0.05 making 20 bins in total. Generally, in these kind of analyses, the number of bins is decided according to the number of observations, and it is between n^1/2 and n/4 where n is the number of observations. However, in this case, due to the very low number of observations in the bins, it is decided to decrease the number of bins to make the analyses statistically significant. Moreover, the range is adjusted according to the minimum and the maximum implied over probabilities to eliminate the bins with zero observations. Additionally, the bins are modified such that each of them have more than 4 observations because otherwise the results would not be statistically significant again with very few observations in the bins.

After these calculations, the performance of the bookmakers will be tested by plotting the implied over probability average versus the estimated probability of overs. For a successful bookmaker, it would be expected to see the points around x=y line which would show the bookmaker is good at setting the over odds.

Section A

In this part, 5 bookmakers that have over/under odds are selected, and their performances on both final and initial bets are evaluated. In the data, it can be seen that there are more than one bet for each match with the indicated timestamps because the odds may change due to injuries, team conditions, red-card penalties from previous matches, etc. In this task, the concentration will be on the initial over bets and final over bets.

With the following code, the selection for the bets are done. The over probabilities are calculated. However, the implied probabilities will be calculated in the coming parts.

data_ou <- data_odds[oddtype == "over" | oddtype == "under"]
data_ou <- data_ou[totalhandicap == 2.5]
data_ou$prob <- 1/(data_ou$odd)  #calculating over probabilities
data_overs <- data_ou[oddtype == "over"]
data_unders <- data_ou[oddtype == "under"]

For this task, 5 bookmakers are selected such that they have the highest number of over bets for the matches.

bookmaker_list <- data_overs[, .N, by = .(bookmaker)]

Bookmaker 1 (10Bet)

Performance on Final Probabilities

Firstly, the performance of 10Bet on final odds will be evaluated. Therefore, the odds with the highest timestamps are chosen.

selected_bookmakers1_final <- selected_bookmakers1[, .SD[which.max(date)], 
    by = matchId]
bm1_under_final <- bm1_under[, .SD[which.max(date)], by = matchId]

The final implied over probabilities of 10Bet are calculated with the formula stated in the Task 1 part.

under_prob <- bm1_under_final[, `:=`(under_prob, prob)]
under_prob <- under_prob[, .(matchId, under_prob)]
selected_bookmakers1_final <- left_join(selected_bookmakers1_final, 
    under_prob, by = c(matchId = "matchId"))
# calculating implying probabilities
selected_bookmakers1_final$implied <- (selected_bookmakers1_final$prob)/(selected_bookmakers1_final$prob + 
    selected_bookmakers1_final$under_prob)

Afterwards, by using the score information from data_matches dataset, whether a match is finished over or not is determined. As mentioned earlier, 2.5 goals is selected as threshold while specifying the the over condition of the matches. A new is_over column is added as the indicator after comparing the total number of goals with 2.5. In the data, there are also matches which have not been played yet. These matches are omitted since the over or under information is not available.

score_info <- data_matches[, .(matchId, score)]
# combining the score information of the matches with the
# odds and probabilities
selected_bookmakers1_final <- left_join(selected_bookmakers1_final, 
    score_info, by = c(matchId = "matchId"))
# omitting not-finished matches
selected_bookmakers1_final <- na.omit(selected_bookmakers1_final, 
    cols = "score", invert = FALSE)
# adjusting the score column
selected_bookmakers1_final <- selected_bookmakers1_final %>% 
    separate(score, c("home_goals", "away_goals"), ":")
selected_bookmakers1_final$home_goals <- as.numeric(selected_bookmakers1_final$home_goals)
selected_bookmakers1_final$away_goals <- as.numeric(selected_bookmakers1_final$away_goals)
selected_bookmakers1_final$total_goals <- selected_bookmakers1_final$home_goals + 
    selected_bookmakers1_final$away_goals
# making comparison and adding 'is_over column'
selected_bookmakers1_final <- as.data.frame(selected_bookmakers1_final)
selected_bookmakers1_final[, "is_over"] <- lapply(selected_bookmakers1_final, 
    FUN = function(x) ifelse(selected_bookmakers1_final$total_goals > 
        2.5, 1, 0))

After this step, the probability range is determined. As the first step in specifying the bins, the minimum and the maximum of the implied over probabilities are checked. As it can be seen below, the minimum implied probability is 0.2812, and the maximum is 0.7857. Therefore, the range will be (0.25,0.30],(0.30,0.35],,(0.75,0.80] with the number of 11 bins in total.

The count array keeps the total number of matches, the avg array keeps the sum of the implied over probabilities and the num_over array keeps the number of matches that finished over in the corresponding bin.

# checking the minimum and the maximum
summary(selected_bookmakers1_final$implied)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2812  0.4599  0.5053  0.5119  0.5591  0.7857
# creating bins
range_over <- 0.25
for (i in 6:16) {
    range_over <- c(range_over, i/20)
}
count <- array(0, 11)
avg <- array(0, 11)
num_over <- array(0, 11)

for (j in 1:nrow(selected_bookmakers1_final)) {
    for (k in 1:11) {
        if (selected_bookmakers1_final[j, 10] > range_over[k] & 
            selected_bookmakers1_final[j, 10] <= range_over[k + 
                1]) {
            count[k] <- count[k] + 1
            avg[k] <- avg[k] + selected_bookmakers1_final[j, 
                10]
            if (selected_bookmakers1_final[j, 14] == 1) {
                num_over[k] <- num_over[k] + 1
            }
            break
        }
    }
}
# checking the number of observations in each bin
count
##  [1]   1  18 105 447 758 690 464 201  90  27   7

Here, the number of observations in count arrays are checked in order the results to be meaningful. As it can be seen above, the first element in the count array do not have enough observations. Therefore, the first and the second bins are merged. There is no need to do any further merges. The new probability range is (0.25,0.35],(0.35,0.40],,(0.75,0.80].

count[2] <- count[2] + count[1]
avg[2] <- avg[2] + avg[1]
num_over[2] <- num_over[2] + num_over[1]
count <- count[2:11]
avg <- avg[2:11]
num_over <- num_over[2:11]

As the final step before plotting, the fraction of games finished over for the corresponding bin and the implied over probability average in bins are calculated.

for (k in 1:length(count)) {
    avg[k] <- avg[k]/count[k]
    num_over[k] <- num_over[k]/count[k]
}

Finally, the scatter plot of final implied over probability average versus the estimated probabilities of overs is shown below:

color <- seq(1, length(count))
plot(avg, num_over, col = color, xlim = c(0.15, 1), ylim = c(0.15, 
    1), lwd = 2, pch = 16, xlab = "Implied Over Probability Averages", 
    ylab = "The Fraction of Games Finished Over", main = "The Scatter Plot of Implied Probability Averages vs Estimated Probabilities", 
    cex.main = 0.75, cex.lab = 0.75, cex.axis = 0.75, sub = "Figure 1: Final Probabilities of 10Bet")
legend("topleft", c("(0.25-0.35]", "(0.35-0.40]", "(0.40-0.45]", 
    "(0.45-0.50]", "(0.50-0.55]", "(0.55-0.60]", "(0.60-0.65]", 
    "(0.65-0.70]", "(0.70-0.75]", "(0.75-0.80]"), col = color, 
    cex = 0.6, pch = 16)
abline(0, 1, col = 100)

As it can be seen from the scatter plot, the points in the inside part are considerably on the x=y line which indicates that this bookmaker is good at setting odds for over bets. However, there are some deviations from the line in the first bin and the last two bins. When the count array is checked, it can be seen that they have relatively small number of observations compared to the inside bins. Therefore, the conclusion from the inside bins are more statistically significant. Also, it may be due to the bookmakers desire to make money. When the probability of the match finishing over is very low, the odd would be very high. However, the bookmaker may adjust this high odd by diminishing slightly; so that, people assume that team is not that low likely to win the match. Hence, the implied over probability average is higher than the estimated probability for the (0.25,0.35] bin.

Another reason can be that the bookmaker may want to increase the number of people betting on the matches with high over probabilities also; so that, the bookmaker increases the odds a little because there is also chance of the match finishing under even though it is less probable.

As it can be seen below, the first element in the count array does not have enough observations. Therefore, the first two bins are merged. There is no need to do any further merges. The new probability range is (0.30,0.40],(0.40,0.45],,(0.65,0.70].

Section B

In this section, the objective is to evaluate if a bookmaker is consistently good at determining over probabilities. Therefore, the task is to repeat the analysis of Section A for each year from 2010 to 2018. bet365 is chosen for this task since their performance on the final odds is concluded to be the best among 5 bookmakers.

The first task is to divide the match instances into the subset of the corresponding year:

selected_bookmakers4_final$time <- as.POSIXct(as.numeric(selected_bookmakers4_final$date), 
    origin = "1970-01-01", tz = "GMT")
selected_bookmakers4_final <- selected_bookmakers4_final %>% 
    separate(time, c("year", "rest"), "-")

    with = FALSE]

summary(selected_bookmakers4_final$implied)

Here, it can be seen that the minimum implied over probability is 0.3049, and the maximum is 0.7830. Therefore, the range for the years is (0.30,0.35],(0.35,0.40],,(0.75,0.80] with the number of 10 bins in total.

Below, count_time matrix keeps the total number of matches in the corresponding bin in rows of the corresponding year in columns. num_over_time matrix keeps the number of matches that finished over in the corresponding bin of the corresponding year. On the other hand, avg_time matrix keeps the cumulative implied probabilities in the corresponding bin of the corresponding year.

range_over_time <- 0.3
for (i in 7:16) {
    range_over_time <- c(range_over_time, i/20)
}

# creating the matrices over time for interested statistics
years <- as.data.frame(years)
count_time = matrix(rep(c(0), each = 10 * 9), nrow = 10, ncol = 9)
colnames(count_time) <- years[, 1]
avg_time = matrix(rep(c(0), each = 10 * 9), nrow = 10, ncol = 9)
colnames(avg_time) <- years[, 1]
num_over_time = matrix(rep(c(0), each = 10 * 9), nrow = 10, ncol = 9)
colnames(num_over_time) <- years[, 1]
selected_bookmakers4_final <- as.data.frame(selected_bookmakers4_final)

for (j in 1:nrow(selected_bookmakers4_final)) {
    for (k in 1:10) {
        if (selected_bookmakers4_final[j, 10] > range_over_time[k] & 
            selected_bookmakers4_final[j, 10] < range_over_time[k + 
                1]) {
            year <- selected_bookmakers4_final[j, 15]
            count_time[k, year] <- count_time[k, year] + 1
            avg_time[k, year] <- avg_time[k, year] + selected_bookmakers4_final[j, 
                8]
            if (selected_bookmakers4_final[j, 14] == 1) {
                num_over_time[k, year] <- num_over_time[k, year] + 
                  1
            }
            break
        }
    }
}

Here, the number of observations in count_time matrix should be checked in order the results to be statistically significant.

According to the count matrix, the mergings should be done as follows similar to the previous parts:

  1. for 2010: no need to combine any bin since there is only 1 observation.

  2. for 2011: combine 2,3 and 8,9

  3. for 2012: combine 2,3

  4. for 2013: combine 1,2 and 8,9

  5. for 2014: combine 8,9

  6. for 2015: combine 1,2 and 8,9

  7. for 2016: combine 8,9

  8. for 2017: combine 9,10

  9. for 2018: combine 1,2 and 9,10

So that each bin will have more than 4 observations. The other mergings for the remaining years are perfomed in a similar manner.

# mergings: 2011
count_time[3, 2] <- count_time[2, 2] + count_time[3, 2]

As the final step before plotting, the fraction of games finished over for the corresponding bin and the implied over probability average in bins are calculated.

for (k in 1:10) {
    for (m in 1:9) {
        avg_time[k, m] <- avg_time[k, m]/count_time[k, m]
        num_over_time[k, m] <- num_over_time[k, m]/count_time[k, 
            m]
    }
}

In the plotting part, the objective is to evaluate the performance of bet365 over the years. When the bins are merged, no observation have been left in the 0.75-0.80 bin; so that it is not included in the plots.

In (0.35-0.40], there are fluctuations, and there is no constant improvement. The best performance for this bin is in 2014. In (0.40-0.45] bin, the performance in 2010 seems very bad, but when it is checked, it is due to the single number of observation in that year. However, except 2017, the performance is overall good over the years. The best performance is in 2011, and in the other years except 2010 and 2017, the performance is similar. The other plots (Figure 12 and Figure 13) are drawn in a similar way.

In this plot, there are bins within 0.45-0.60 range. In (0.45,0.50] bin, the performance is consistently good in the initial years. However, the performace after 2016 worsened a bit. In (0.50,0.55] bin, the performance in 2012, 2013, 2015 and 2016 is very good. On the other hand, there are small fluctuations in the remaining years. In (0.55-0.60] bin, the situation is similar. There are some years where the performance is fluctuating and in 2011 and 2016, the performance is very good. Overall, the performance of Betclic in 2016 is the best among the years for these 3 bins. In the remaining years, the performance is average. One more thing to mention is that the performance in 2018 is the worst for these bins.

In this plot, there are bins within 0.60-0.75 range. In (0.60-0.65] bin, the performance is good in years from 2011 to 2013. Then, it gets worse for 2 years, and it improves again. In (0.65-0.70] bin, except 2012 and 2013, the performance is consistently good. In (0.70-0.75] bin, there are only observations from 2012, 2017 and 2018. Hence, when 2017 and 2018 are compared, the performance improved in 2018.

In conclusion, it cannot be said that the performance of bet365 is consistently good at determining the over probabilities since there are some fluctuations among the years.

Task 2

The objective in this task is to capture the information that may come from the change in the odds for match results. The scatterplots from the lattice package can be helpful in this study since it also allows categorical variable (odd types in this scenario) breakdowns easily.

First, the subset of the matches that have match result odd information is chosen. The bookmaker having the highest number of odd information is Betclic, and the analysis is going to be continued based on the odds from Betclic.

library(lattice)
library(gridExtra)  #the necessary libraries for this task
data_result <- data_odds[betType == "1x2"]
bookmakers <- data_result[, .N, keyby = .(bookmaker)]
bookmakers <- bookmakers[order(-N)]
betclic <- data_result[bookmaker == "Betclic"]

Betclic has odds information for 3084 matches in total where the odd changes can be analyzed for match results. However, for simplicity, 4 of them will be selected randomly and analyzed in terms of odd changes.

matches <- betclic[, .N, keyby = .(matchId)]
matches <- matches[order(-N)]
# random match ID's
match1 <- betclic[matchId == matches[208, 1]]  #score:(1:0)
match2 <- betclic[matchId == matches[229, 1]]  #score:(2:0)
match3 <- betclic[matchId == matches[273, 1]]  #score:(1:2)
match4 <- betclic[matchId == matches[257, 1]]  #score:(2:2)

In the plots, the x axis will show the time information starting with the time of the first odds for that particular match and ending with the time of the last odds. On the other hand, the y axis has odd information. The breakdown is based on the oddtypes; so that the changes in the home-win, tie and away-win odds can be analyzed seperately since they can provide different information. The plots are given below:

plot1 <- xyplot(odd ~ as.POSIXct(date, origin = "1970-01-01") | 
    oddtype, data = match1, main = "The Odd Changes for the Match: Burnley-Watford", 
    xlab = "Time", ylab = "Odd", grid = TRUE, pch = 1, cex = 1.2, 
    col = rgb(0.2, 0.4, 0.8, 0.5))
plot2 <- xyplot(odd ~ as.POSIXct(date, origin = "1970-01-01") | 
    oddtype, data = match2, main = "The Odd Changes for the Match: Everton-Huddersfield", 
    xlab = "Time", ylab = "Odd", grid = TRUE, pch = 1, cex = 1.2, 
    col = rgb(0.2, 0.4, 0.8, 0.5))
plot3 <- xyplot(odd ~ as.POSIXct(date, origin = "1970-01-01") | 
    oddtype, data = match3, main = "The Odd Changes for the Match: Watford-Manchester United",

plot1

Here it can be seen that at first, the first team was thought to be more likely to win the match, so that home-win odds is less. However, as the time passed, the bookmaker increased the odds for home-win and therefore decreased the odds for away-win which may be due to an injury in the home team or etc. In the time between, the odds fluctuated slightly. In the end, it seems that two are equally likely to win the match. The score of the match is 1-0, so the bookmaker should not have increased the odds for home-win.

For this match, it can be seen from the very low odds that the home team was favourite to win. The odds for the home-win case did not change too much, whereas the odds for away-win decreased a little until the match with some fluctuations. It was obvious from the odds that if no surprise happens, the first team would win, and the score was 1-0.

From this plot, it can be seen that in 2-week period, the odds continuously changed. For this match, the away-team was favourite, and juft before the match the odds for away-win decreased even more. It may be due to any unexpected condition again for the home-team. The bookmaker did well on setting the odds for this match because the score was 1-2.

From the last plot, it can be seen that in 10-day period before the match, the conditions did not change so much that odds remained constant. However, in the last days, some small fluctuations happened, but the home-team remained the favourite. As it can be observed, the difference in the odds of home-win and away-win is not as much as the second match above which means the difference in the likelihood of one team winning is not too much, and the match ended as 2-2.

In order to analyze the odd changes, I chose this type of plot where each match can be observed seperately since each match has unique set of conditions such as team players, injuries, red cards etc. There may be for sure other ways to explore the changes in the odds.
